\par \pard\plain \s38\sa120\nowidctlpar \f4\lang2057 To be able to write Java programs in {\i Pow! }you have to {\strike\cf11 download}{\v\cf11 DownloadingJava} and install Suns Java Development Kit (JDK) first. This release of {\i Pow! }
has been tested in combination with JDK 1.1.5 and 1.1.6. It is very likely that {\i Pow! }will also work in combination with newer releases without changes, because there the interdependency between the JDK and {\i Pow!} is very limited.
\par After you have installed both {\i Pow!} and the JDK, you need to {\strike\cf11 set up }{\i\strike\cf11 Pow!}{\v\cf11 SetupJava}{\i  }to make it aware of where you installed the JDK.
\par When you create a project for a Java application in {\i Pow! }you have to be very care
ful to use exactly the same name for the project and the main class. Because Java is case sensitive this means that the project file name has to be defined with the same usage of upper and lower case as the Java class name. 
\par The easiest way to create a Java project is to use one of the Java templates. There is one for Java Applications and Java Applets. Click on the menu entry \ldblquote New..\rdblquote  in the menu \ldblquote Project\rdblquote 
 and select the desired template. After entering the location and name of the new project Pow! creates a new project.
